The lipophilicity of EOs enable them to preferentially part
from an aqueous phase into membrane structures of the fungi,
resulting in expansion of membrane, and then increase of
membrane ﬂuidity and permeability, disturbance of membrane-
embedded proteins and soluble sugars, and other cellular
contents. The electric conductivity was examined to express
the changes of CM permeability. Our results showed that the
extracellular conductivity rose with the increasing of CEO
concentration and treatment time. The results clearly indicated
that there was a leakage of electrolytes due to the disruption
of cell permeability caused by CEO. Excessive electrolyte loss
control might be due to regular fungal cytolysis and death, just
of the cytoplasmic membrane is a critical factor to fungal
growth. Analyzing the leakage of cell constituents could therefore
give further insight into the mechanism of antifungal action.
